{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"202"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/202"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.12,0.05,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107693"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/202"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"246"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"4535"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107693"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of intermittent episodes of palpitations, sweating and feeling faint. He used to enjoy an early morning jog around the park before breakfast, but these seem to bring on his symptoms and he has now stopped jogging after his wife began worrying about his confused state upon returning home. Once he had sat down and had a glass of orange juice with breakfast, his symptoms seemed to resolve. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker and enjoys two glasses of wine a day. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 22 kg/m\u00b2. Examination of his chest and abdomen is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be abnormal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fasting blood glucose","Urinary catecholamines","Thyroid function tests","Holter monitor","ECG"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of hypoglycaemia triggered by fasting and exercise, which resolve with glucose administration. This pattern strongly suggests an insulinoma, a rare pancreatic tumour that secretes excessive insulin. The key diagnostic clue is the relationship between symptoms and fasting states, particularly exercise before breakfast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting blood glucose\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most revealing investigation, as it would demonstrate hypoglycaemia during symptomatic episodes. A glucose level below 2.8 mmol/L (2.2-11.1) with concurrent symptoms that resolve with glucose administration would satisfy Whipple\u0027s triad, supporting the diagnosis of insulinoma and prompting further investigations such as insulin levels and abdominal imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary catecholamines\u003C/strong\u003E are used to diagnose phaeochromocytoma, which can present with similar symptoms of palpitations and sweating. However, phaeochromocytoma episodes are typically not related to fasting or exercise, do not resolve with glucose administration, and are often associated with severe hypertension during attacks. The clear relationship between this patient\u0027s symptoms and fasting states makes phaeochromocytoma unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E would be abnormal in hyperthyroidism, which can cause palpitations and sweating. However, hyperthyroid symptoms are typically persistent rather than episodic, and would not be specifically triggered by fasting or relieved by glucose intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHolter monitor\u003C/strong\u003E would detect cardiac arrhythmias that could cause palpitations and feeling faint. However, the clear temporal relationship with fasting and resolution with glucose makes a primary cardiac cause unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E might show evidence of structural heart disease or arrhythmias, but given the episodic nature of symptoms and their relationship to fasting, a resting ECG would likely be normal and would not explain the glucose-responsive symptom pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An insulinoma is a rare, but important cause of hypoglycaemia."],"references":["Tucker ON, Crotty PL, Conlon KC. The management of insulinoma. Br J Surg. 2006 Mar 1;93(3), 264\u2013275.","Okabayashi T, Shima Y, Sumiyoshi T, Kozuki A, Ito S, Ogawa Y, et al. Diagnosis and management of insulinoma. World J Gastroenterol. 2013 Feb 14;19(6):829-37."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90125"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"202"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90125"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-02T08:06:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-02T08:07:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type"